coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aIn the summer of 2015, an extraordinary number of German residents felt an urge to provide help to refugees. Doing good, however, is not as simple and straightforward as it might appear. Practices of solidarity are intertwined with questions of power. They are situated, relative and contested, unfolding in an ambivalent space between humanitarianism and political activism. This ethnographic account of the German »welcome culture« provides insights into the contested practices, imaginaries, interests and politics of refugee solidarity. Drawing on works from critical migration studies to social anthropology, Larissa Fleischmann develops an empirically grounded understanding of solidarity in migration societies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aRefugeesxGovernment policyzGermany. 4aCivil Society. 4aFleeing. 4aHumanitarianism. 4aMigration Policy. 4aMigration. 4aPolitical Activism. 4aPolitics. 4aRefugee Studies. 4aSocial Movements. 4aSolidarity. 4aVolunteering. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Emigration & Immigration.2bisacsh  aCivil Society.  aFleeing.  aHumanitarianism.  aMigration Policy.  aMigration.  aPolitical Activism.  aPolitics.  aRefugee Studies.  aSocial Movements.  aSolidarity.  aVolunteering.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus PP Package 2020 Part 2z978311069629508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK 